             <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1" resp="RED2007">
                <p><title>Ogham</title>: of <persName xml:lang="pgl">Maqas-Treni Salicidunus/-i</persName></p>
                    </div>
                <div type="textpart" n="2" resp="RED2007">
                    <p><title>Roman</title>: of <persName xml:lang="pgl"> Maccutreni Salicidunus/-i</persName></p>
                    </div>
            </div>
                        <div type="commentary">
                            <p>The name MAQITRENI / [M]ACCVTRENI is Irish and the same as that inscribed on Llywel (Crai) B41. According to the Welsh Corpus this could <q>conceivably [be] the same person (if so, he must be named as the father, rather than the deceased, on at least one of the two stones!)</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 238) The two stones could indicate the placement of the estate of Maccutrenus or they could have <q>formed the nucleus of an early Christian burial-ground</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 238). However, this is not certain as the name also appears to have been popular in Britain and Ireland. The second element of the name may be related to Welsh <foreign xml:lang="cy">trwyn</foreign> in the name <persName>Cyndrwyn</persName>. On the second half of the inscription, the Welsh Corpus notes that <q>'SALICIDUNI / SALICIDVNI may be Welsh or Irish... the name means 'willow fort', and could be a personal name or a place-name, Salicidunum, associated with the deceased</q> (Redknap and Lewis 2007, 238). On the context of this stone, the Welsh Corpus notes that <q>this stone belongs to a small group (Crickhowell 1 (B2), Defynnog 1(B4), Llywel 1 (B41) and Trallwng 1 (B45)) in the Upper Usk Valley commemorating men with Irish names, some of which are also found in north-west Pembrokeshire (Nash-Williams 1950, no 425)</q>.</p>
                        </div>
